---
import MainLayout from "../../layouts/MainLayout.astro";

const pageTitle = "When the System Resets: Institutional Knowledge During Platform Transitions";
const pageDescription =
  "A reflection on institutional knowledge, platform transitions, and what system resets reveal in research administration.";
const publishDate = "March 25, 2026";
---

<MainLayout title={pageTitle} description={pageDescription}>
  <section class="blog-post-shell">
    <div class="blog-post-inner">
      <img
        class="blog-hero-image"
        src="/assets/page-under-transition.png"
        alt="Cartoon sign reading Page Under Transition with barricades and worksite elements"
      />

      <header class="article-header">
        <p class="article-eyebrow">Blog</p>
        <h1>{pageTitle}</h1>
        <p class="article-date">{publishDate}</p>
        <p class="article-disclaimer">
          <em>
            This essay draws upon my experience and expertise within research
            administration systems. Rather than evaluating a specific platform or
            institutional decision, it examines broader themes and recurring dynamics
            that arise during system transitions.
          </em>
        </p>
      </header>

      <article class="article-card">
        <p>
          Institutions routinely adopt new platforms to modernize operations,
          motivated by requirements such as regulatory compliance, system integration,
          or scalability.
        </p>

        <p>
          In my current environment, this transition is underway. However, the
          dynamics surrounding such shifts are not unique; they reflect a broader
          pattern that emerges whenever an institution replaces a system upon which it
          has become dependent.
        </p>

        <p>
          This is because the change involves more than just the technological tool.
        </p>

        <p>
          What changes, at least temporarily, is the role of institutional knowledge.
        </p>

        <h2>What Institutional Knowledge Actually Is</h2>

        <p>
          Institutional knowledge is often equated with experience, but it is more
          specific. It does not consist of documentation or training materials.
          Rather, it comprises the accumulation of nuanced, repeated understandings
          that develop over time.
        </p>

        <p>
          It involves anticipating where errors are likely to occur, distinguishing
          which processes adhere to documented procedures, and identifying those that
          rely on informal workarounds. It also encompasses understanding whom to
          consult, when to seek guidance, and how to interpret responses within the
          context of a system that may not always function predictably.
        </p>

        <p>
          This type of knowledge is rarely formalized, yet it is essential for the
          smooth functioning of systems.
        </p>

        <h2>The Reset Moment</h2>

        <p>
          When a new platform is introduced, accumulated institutional knowledge does
          not transfer seamlessly.
        </p>

        <p>
          The interface and underlying logic are altered. Pathways that previously
          felt intuitive may no longer exist. Consequently, both experienced staff
          and new hires must navigate an unfamiliar environment.
        </p>

        <p>
          This process can resemble starting anew.
        </p>

        <p>
          More precisely, it constitutes a return to the same interface, but not to
          the same level of understanding.
        </p>

        <p>
          Experience does not vanish; rather, what changes is the manner in which
          that experience can be applied.
        </p>

        <h2>What Gets Disrupted</h2>

        <p>
          During transitions, certain types of knowledge temporarily lose their
          practical utility.
        </p>

        <p>
          Efficiency is among the first aspects affected. Tasks that previously
          required minimal time now take significantly longer as users reacquaint
          themselves with system navigation and process workflows. Shortcuts based on
          prior system familiarity become obsolete. To mitigate this slowdown, teams
          may establish peer support channels or develop quick reference guides to
          ensure prompt responses to questions and facilitate access to new
          procedures. Pairing experienced staff with new users or conducting brief
          daily check-ins during initial launch periods can further support
          collaborative problem-solving and the timely sharing of discoveries before
          they develop into bottlenecks.
        </p>

        <p>
          System-specific intuition is also disrupted. The expectation that processes
          will function as they previously did becomes less reliable when the
          underlying structure has changed.
        </p>

        <p>
          This disruption can temporarily diminish the visibility of expertise, as it
          can no longer be demonstrated through previously established actions.
        </p>

        <h2>What Remains</h2>

        <p>
          At the same time, other forms of knowledge remain intact.
        </p>

        <p>
          Judgment is not reset. The capacity to recognize risk, anticipate issues,
          and comprehend the implications of decisions persists, even when the system
          itself is unfamiliar.
        </p>

        <p>
          Pattern recognition also endures. Although the interface may be new, the
          nature of the problems encountered is often familiar. Experienced staff can
          continue to identify inconsistencies, gaps, and areas requiring
          clarification.
        </p>

        <p>
          Most importantly, the ability to navigate ambiguity becomes increasingly
          apparent. When the system no longer provides clarity, individuals who are
          adept at asking questions, validating assumptions, and adapting in real
          time become essential.
        </p>

        <h2>What the Reset Reveals</h2>

        <p>
          System transitions do more than disrupt workflows; they also reveal the
          underlying structure of organizational processes.
        </p>

        <p>
          Processes that relied on individual knowledge become harder to sustain.
          Informal workarounds that used to compensate for system limitations are no
          longer available. Unspoken assumptions are brought to the surface. Teams
          can proactively hold discussions or map process flows together to uncover
          these hidden assumptions. For example, inviting staff to walk through their
          steps during real scenarios can reveal inconsistencies or knowledge gaps.
          Making these assumptions visible allows administrators to anticipate
          friction points and adjust support or documentation accordingly.
        </p>

        <p>
          Although this process may be uncomfortable, it also provides valuable
          clarity.
        </p>

        <p>
          It creates an opportunity to differentiate between elements that were
          system-dependent and those that were structurally robust.
        </p>

        <h2>Working Through the Transition</h2>

        <p>
          Successfully navigating a system transition requires a shift in approach.
        </p>

        <p>
          Clarity becomes more valuable than confidence. It is more effective to
          delineate what is known, unknown, and requires confirmation, rather than
          relying on habits that may no longer be applicable.
        </p>

        <p>
          Documentation becomes iterative rather than static. Instead of waiting for
          processes to stabilize, it is necessary to document evolving understanding
          as it develops.
        </p>

        <p>
          Questions shift from being perceived as a sign of uncertainty to becoming
          an essential component of maintaining accuracy. Asking questions early and
          frequently reduces the risk of compounding errors during the learning phase
          of the new system.
        </p>

        <p>
          Roles may also require redefinition. When previous expertise becomes less
          visible, clarity regarding responsibilities and expectations becomes
          increasingly important. For example, a subject matter expert who previously
          addressed nuanced system-specific questions may transition into a process
          coach, assisting colleagues in interpreting new workflows and adapting
          daily practices. Instead of relying on knowledge of former system
          shortcuts, they support the team by facilitating discussions, identifying
          learning gaps, and raising questions that highlight areas of the new
          system requiring further attention. This shift in role repositions
          expertise as the cultivation of shared understanding during the transition,
          rather than simply possessing the correct answers.
        </p>

        <div class="closing-card">
          <p>
            Looking ahead, this reset represents more than an opportunity to
            navigate disruption; it serves as a catalyst for institutional growth.
          </p>
          <p>
            By leveraging transitions to reevaluate processes, capture lessons
            learned, and foster collaboration across roles, administrators can
            strengthen both their systems and the foundation of shared knowledge.
          </p>
          <p>
            Approaching change with curiosity and a commitment to learning ensures
            that institutional memory is actively cultivated, resulting in a more
            resilient and adaptive organization.
          </p>
        </div>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>
</MainLayout>

<style>
  .blog-post-shell {
    padding: 2.5rem 1.25rem 5rem;
  }

  .blog-post-inner {
    max-width: 860px;
    margin: 0 auto;
  }

  .blog-hero-image {
    width: 100%;
    height: 320px;
    object-fit: cover;
    display: block;
    border-radius: 1.4rem;
    margin-bottom: 1.75rem;
    box-shadow: 0 18px 40px rgba(15, 23, 42, 0.08);
  }

  .article-header {
    margin-bottom: 1.4rem;
  }

  .article-eyebrow {
    margin: 0 0 0.45rem;
    font-size: 0.76rem;
    letter-spacing: 0.14em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: #5f6b76;
  }

  .article-header h1 {
    margin: 0;
    font-family: Cambria, Georgia, "Times New Roman", serif;
    font-size: clamp(2rem, 4vw, 3rem);
    line-height: 1.12;
    color: #16342d;
  }

  .article-date {
    margin: 0.7rem 0 0.55rem;
    font-size: 0.98rem;
    color: #667085;
  }

  .article-disclaimer {
    margin: 0;
    font-size: 0.98rem;
    line-height: 1.6;
    color: #667085;
  }

  .article-card {
    background: #ffffff;
    border: 1px solid rgba(38, 78, 65, 0.08);
    border-radius: 1.5rem;
    padding: clamp(1.5rem, 3vw, 2.4rem);
    box-shadow: 0 20px 50px rgba(15, 23, 42, 0.06);
  }

  .article-card p {
    margin: 0 0 1.15rem;
    font-size: 1.04rem;
    line-height: 1.82;
    color: #22313a;
  }

  .article-card h2 {
    margin: 2rem 0 0.85rem;
    font-family: Cambria, Georgia, "Times New Roman", serif;
    font-size: clamp(1.45rem, 2.5vw, 1.9rem);
    line-height: 1.2;
    color: #16342d;
  }

  .closing-card {
    margin-top: 2.2rem;
    padding: 1.4rem 1.35rem;
    background: #f7faf9;
    border: 1px solid rgba(38, 78, 65, 0.12);
    border-left: 4px solid #264e41;
    border-radius: 1.05rem;
  }

  .closing-card p:last-child {
    margin-bottom: 0;
  }

  @media (max-width: 720px) {
    .blog-hero-image {
      height: 240px;
    }

    .blog-post-shell {
      padding-top: 1.5rem;
    }
  }
</style>